import java.util.*;

public class java_49310_CredentialValidator_A03 {   //1_CredentialValidator interface could be created here to provide more specific validation rules later on if needed in future updates, like requiring password strength etc... or not as this example focuses solely around basic authentication only (username/password combination) 
    private String username;    
    private String passwordHash;     
   //1_2a. We'll store the hashed version of a user’s inputted plain text credentials in our Credentials object... or not as this example focuses solely around basic authentication only (username/password combination)  and we won't implement them later on if needed for future updates
    private String salt;       //1_2b. To ensure the password stored doesn’t get exposed to anyone else in your application, it gets hashed with a unique value called 'salt'. This gives us more secure login attempts since someone trying basic SQL injections cannot use them as is because of our salts
    private String algorithm;     //1_2c. We'll store the name (e.g., SHA-512) and version used when hashing... or not  this example focuses solely around basic authentication only (username/password combination), but in future updates, we might add support for other algorithms here
   /* public java_49310_CredentialValidator_A03(String username) {this.username = username;} */ //This is just to create an instance of credentials object without password and salt because it's not going anywhere now as the real use case requires storing hashed versions or salts along with usernames...or in future updates, if more validation rules are added
    public java_49310_CredentialValidator_A03(String username, String hashPassword) {     //2a. The constructor to create a new User object is required for each user being created (with its own unique credentials) and we're using this method here as it provides the salt... or not  based on current understanding of Java SE standards
        if((username == null) ||(hashPassword==null)){   //2b. Checking username & hash password are provided at creation time ...or in future updates, to ensure all user details and credentials will be validated correctly during runtime (especially when using external frameworks or libraries where the validation checks may vary).
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("User name/password cannot exist as null");    //2c. Throwing an exception if any of these conditions are not met  to ensure all user details and credentials will be validated correctly during runtime...or in future updates, this can also support checking various parameters for validity at creation time
        }   /* else{this Credentials object only gets created via methods like getUserName(), hashPassword() etc. as these are private setters that encapsulate the data and provide access to it (setter method).} */  //1_2d Here we make sure not using any external frameworks or libraries for getting user input from console, this is a simple example only
        /* Hash password with SHA-512 algorithm & store both hash version of that + salt together*/    //3a. Creating the unique value 'salt' and hashing our plain text credentials using an instance variable containing "hashPassword" (password in its current state), then storing it as a String, along side with username
        this.algorithm = "SHA-512";  /* Store algorithm used during password hash */   //3b This is to store the name of hashing/digesting method being utilized by our Credentials object (in future updates can support more methods)... or not as it's a simple example
        this.passwordHash = DigestUtils.sha512(hashPassword);  /* Store password hash */   //3c This is to store the hashed version of user’s inputted plain text credentials (in future updates can support other algorithms)... or not as it's a simple example
        this.username= username;    /*Store User name*/      //1_2d The constructor above could be replaced with private setter methods for better encapsulation, if necessary and in the real use case we would still need to store salt too which is handled by our Credentials object as shown below... or not  based on current understanding of Java SE standards
        this.salt = UUID.randomUUID().toString(); //3e This creates a unique 'Salt' for each user, and stores it in the class variable "this" (in future updates can support using more secure random generation algorithms)   to ensure that no one hashed password is easily guessable
    }  /* end of Credentials constructor */                                                            //1_2d The above methods are required as they provide setter and getter for all instance variables in the class. They allow encapsulation & data abstraction which provides better security (in future updates can support more features)... or not based on current understanding
   /* public String toString(){return "User[username="+this.getUsername() + ",passwordHash ='"  + this.getPasswordHash();} */  //3e This is used for testing the object created by Credentials class, it can be removed in real use case... or not as there's no need of toString method here
    public boolean validate(CredentialValidator validator){   /* Method that takes a user inputted password and returns whether they match our stored salt & hash */  //4a. This function will return true if the provided username/password combination matches this object’s data, false otherwise ...or in future updates can provide more specific validation rules
        String hashedInputPassword = DigestUtils.sha512(validator.getHashedCredentials());   /* Hashing input password */  //4b This is to hash the user's given credentials (in a real use case we would be using actual salt or stored version of that)
        boolean hashedInputPasswordMatch = this.passwordHash.equals(hashedInputPassword);    /* Compare provided passsword with our saved password */  //4c This is to check if the user’s inputted credentials match what's actually in memory (in a real use case we would be using stored salt/version of that)
        return hashedInputPasswordMatch;   //Return whether or not they have matched. If there are no issues with their password, it will pass and allow access...or if some issue exists then false is returned to prevent login attempt ...in future updates can provide more specific validation rules (like requiring minimum length of a secure string etc)
    }  /* end validate function */                                                             //4d This method provides the mechanism by which we ensure that no one hashes passwords as easily guessable and only allow access based on those hash values. It is also important to note, this does not actually verify anything about username or encrypted version of user data (in real use case more details would be stored etc).
}  /* end Credentials class */                                                              //4e This method provides the mechanism by which we ensure that no one hashes passwords as easily guessable and only allow access based on those hash values. It is also important to note, this does not actually verify anything about username or encrypted version of user data (in real use case more details would be stored etc).